CSS Compass was designed with the intention of helping both incoming and current CSS students reach their goals. The development team sought to compile useful resources that they felt aided their own journey, so that new students would have a launchpad for becoming successful students and programmers.

The School of Engineering and Technology (SET) at the University of Washington Tacoma prepares our students to become future leaders in a variety of computer, electrical, mechanical and civil engineering fields. Students enrolled in the SET program go on to develop real world solutions in embedded systems, information technology, information systems, and computer software design, development and maintenance.

Need help with classes in your major? Consider taking a TXXX390 course. These are workshop-style courses that can help you succeed in some of the toughest courses for each of the SET majors. All workshops are numbered 390; for example, TCSS390, TCES390, etc. These workshops offer the opportunity to practice and discuss problems related to specific courses in the core curriculum, and are overseen by a faculty member and a student mentor.
LeetCode is the best platform to help you enhance your skills with coding practice, expand your knowledge and prepare for technical interviews.

The UW Tacoma Teaching and Learning Center (TLC) invites faculty, staff, and students from all backgrounds to join with us in creating a culture of learning. Consultants work collaboratively with students in writing, math, science and statistics, helping them to develop the skills, strategies, knowledge, and confidence necessary for academic success.

The Pantry exists to provide free supplemental, nutritious, and culturally relevant food as well as hygiene items to any UW Tacoma student. The CEI partners with Nourish Pierce County and several other organizations on campus to provide this service and create continued support.

DUBNET is UW Tacoma\'s online home for registered student organizations (RSOs). It is a student engagement platform that helps to keep RSO officers, members, and the general UW Tacoma community connected. Joining an RSO on DUBNET is one of the biggest steps that any student can take to get involved on campus.

UW Tacoma is an urban campus and parking can be a challenge at times. There are a number of paid parking options on and around campus, as well as some free parking options a short walk or light rail ride away.
